\begin_layout Paragraph
Description of technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's follow Herrendorf et al.
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

(2021) by assuming that there are two sectors, goods and services. Goods and services value added, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula \( Y_{gt} \)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( Y_{st} \)
\end_inset

, respectively, are produced according to the Cobb–Douglas production functions 
\begin_inset Formula \[
Y_{jt} = A_{jt} K_{jt}^{\theta} L_{jt}^{1-\theta}, \quad j \in \{g,s\} .
\]
\end_inset

These functions share the same capital intensity, represented by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \theta\in(0,1) \)
\end_inset

, but may have different total factor productivities, 
\begin_inset Formula \( A_{jt} \)
\end_inset

. Production in each sector relies on capital 
\begin_inset Formula \( K_{jt} \)
\end_inset

, and labor 
\begin_inset Formula \( L_{jt} \)
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \in \{g,s\} \)
\end_inset

 indexes the goods and services sectors, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Investment is produced using the CES technology 
\begin_inset Formula \[
I_t = A_{xt} \left( \omega^{\frac{1}{\varepsilon}} X_{gt}^{\frac{\varepsilon - 1}{\varepsilon}} + (1 - \omega)^{\frac{1}{\varepsilon}} X_{st}^{\frac{\varepsilon - 1}{\varepsilon}} \right)^{\frac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon - 1}} ,
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{gt}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{st}$
\end_inset

 represent goods and services inputs, respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \varepsilon \)
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of substitution between them, and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \omega \in(0,1) \)
\end_inset

 determines the weight of sectorial inputs. The state of investment-specific technology is neutral with respect to inputs and represented by the investment specific productivity, 
\begin_inset Formula \( A_{xt} \)
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A representative household has an initial capital stock 
\begin_inset Formula \( K_0 > 0 \)
\end_inset

 and is endowed with one unit of time per period, which is supplied inelastically. Capital depreciates at a rate 
\begin_inset Formula \( \delta >0 \)
\end_inset

, following the law of motion: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:K}
\dot{K}_t = X_t - \delta K_t.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Both capital and labor can move freely between sectors. At equilibrium, the feasibility conditions impose the following constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
K_{gt} + K_{st} = K_t, \quad L_{gt} + L_{st} = 1,
\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{gt} + X_{gt} = Y_{gt}, \quad C_{st} + X_{st} = Y_{st},
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \( C_{gt} \)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( C_{st} \)
\end_inset

 are the consumption of goods and services, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equilibrium prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us adopt the investment good as numeraire. Following Herrendorf et al (2021), it is easy to show that the price of goods, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{gt}$
\end_inset

, relative to the price of services, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{st}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{P_{gt}}{P_{st}} = \frac{A_{st}}{A_{gt}}  ,
\]
\end_inset

is equal to the inverse of the relative sectorial TFPs. Notice that a dupla of production factors 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,L)$
\end_inset

 that produces 
\begin_inset Formula $K^\theta L^{1-\theta} = 1$
\end_inset

 has the same value in the goods and service sectors, since 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{gt} A_{gt}= P_{st} A_{st}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, since we have adopted the investment good as numeraire, the prices of goods and services, relative to the investment good, read 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:Pj}
\boxed{
P_{jt} = \frac{{\cal A}_{t}}{ A_{jt}}, \quad j \in \{g,s\}.
}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:calA}
\boxed{
{\cal A}_{t} = A_{xt} \left( \omega A_{gt}^{\varepsilon - 1} + (1 - \omega) A_{st}^{\varepsilon - 1} \right)^{\frac{1}{\varepsilon - 1}} .
}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

As shown below, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}_{t} $
\end_inset

 is the productivity of the investment sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the investment sector, at equilibrium, the ratio of expenditure shares and input quantities on goods and services are, respectively, given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{P_{gt} X_{gt}}{P_{st} X_{st}} = \frac{\omega}{1 - \omega} \left( \frac{A_{st}}{A_{gt}} \right)^{1 - \varepsilon} 
\ \ \ \ \text{and}\ \ \ \ 
\frac{X_{gt}}{X_{st}} =  \frac{\omega}{1 - \omega} \left( \frac{A_{gt}}{A_{st}} \right)^{ \varepsilon} 
.
\]
\end_inset

Notice that if goods and services are complementary in the investment technology, i.e. 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

, and technical progress is faster in the production of goods, relative to services, then the value added of the goods sector shrinks while real production increases, relative to the service sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Aggregate investment technology. [We can drop this paragarph.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At equilibrium, from Lemma 1 in Herrendorf et al. (2021), the aggregate investment technology is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:investment}
I_t =  {\cal A}_{t} \left( \frac{X_{gt}}{A_{gt}} + \frac{X_{st}}{A_{st}} \right)
= {\cal A}_{t} K_{xt}^{\theta} L_{xt}^{1-\theta} %= {\cal A}_{xt} L_{xt} K_{t}^{\theta}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{xt}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{xt}$
\end_inset

 are defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{xt} = \frac{X_{gt}}{A_{gt} K_t^{\theta}} + \frac{X_{st}}{A_{st} K_t^{\theta}},
\ \ \ \ \text{and}\ \ \ \ 
K_{xt} = L_{xt} K_t .
\]
\end_inset

Let's think on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_x\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 as the fraction of employment and capital allocated to produce inputs for the investment sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
