\begin_layout Paragraph
Non-homothetic preferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The economy features an infinitely lived representative household which preferences are represented by the following utility function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{\infty} U(C_{gt}, C_{st}) \, \text{e}^{-\rho t}\, dt .
\]
\end_inset

The discount rate is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \rho > 0 \)
\end_inset

. The instantaneous utility function 
\begin_inset Formula \( U(\cdot, \cdot) \)
\end_inset

 is assumed to be a price-independent-generalized-linear indirect utility (PIGL henceforth). Since the PIGL class generally lacks a known direct utility representation, we work with its indirect utility formulation 
\begin_inset Formula $v(E_t, P_{gt}, P_{st}) $
\end_inset

. Following Boppart (2014), let us assume 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ass:IUF"

\end_inset

 The instantaneous utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $U(C_{gt}, C_{st})$
\end_inset

 is PIGL with indirect utility representation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:IUF}
V(E_t, P_{gt}, P_{st}) = \frac{1}{\chi}  \left( \frac{E_t}{P_{st}} \right)^\chi - \frac{\eta}{\gamma} \left( \frac{P_{gt}}{P_{st}} \right)^\gamma  - \frac{1}{\chi} + \frac{\eta}{\gamma},
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \(E_t\)
\end_inset

 is consumption expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \eta > 0 \)
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( 1 > \gamma > \chi > 0 \)
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Intertemporal problem and intratemporal allocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under Assumption
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ass:IUF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

, the representative household choses a path 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_t,K_t\}$
\end_inset

, for consumption expenditure and capital, that solves the following dynamic problem 
\begin_inset Formula \[
v(K_t) = \max \int_{0}^{\infty}  \frac{E_t^\chi}{\chi} \, \Gamma_t \, dt 
\]
\end_inset

subject to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:K2}
\boxed{
\dot K_t = {\cal A}_{t} K_t^\theta - E_t - \delta K_t ,
}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where the discount factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_t = P_{st}^{-\chi} \text{e}^{-\rho t}$
\end_inset

, is smaller than one and declining over time since 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{st}$
\end_inset

, as in the data, is assumed to be increasing over time. 
\begin_inset Formula $E_t$
\end_inset

 is nothing else that our measure, in units of the investment good, of total consumption. Preferences are then CIES, with elasticity of substitution larger than one. All other terms in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IUF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) are excluded as they are additive; their discounted integral remains a constant, having no impact on the determination of the optimal path.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Euler equation associated to the household problem above is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:Euler}
\boxed{
\frac{\dot E_t}{E_t} = \frac{1}{1-\chi} \left(\theta {\cal A}_t K_t^{\theta - 1} - \rho - \delta - \chi \frac{\dot P_{st}}{P_{st}}\right) .
}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The equilibrium path solves then (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:K2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Euler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

), given 
\begin_inset Formula $K_0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intratemporal allocation of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_t$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{gt}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{st}$
\end_inset

 results from the use of Roy’s Identity to derive the expenditure share of goods: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:Roy}
\boxed{
\frac{P_{gt} C_{gt}}{E_t} = \eta \left( \frac{E_t}{P_{st}} \right)^{-\chi} \left( \frac{P_{gt}}{P_{st}} \right)^\gamma.
}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The last equation solves for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{gt}$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{st}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained inverting the definition of consumption expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $E_t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
How compute the solution.
