\begin_layout Paragraph
Bellman representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following Duran and Licandro (2025), the Bellman representation of the representative household preferences is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:BR}
W(C_{gt}, C_{st}, X_t;  \nu_t) = U(C_{gt}, C_{st}) + \nu_t X_t ,
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_t = \dot K_t$
\end_inset

 is net investment and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_t$
\end_inset

 is the marginal value of capital at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. In the Bellman representation, preferences at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are indexed by the marginal value of capital 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_t$
\end_inset

. However, it's very important to stress that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_t$
\end_inset

 is not real expenditure but nominal expenditure, and as such it will be our measure of nominal GDP. The representative household maximises (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\{C_g,C_s,X\}$
\end_inset

, subject to the budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P_{gt} C_{gt} + P_{st} C_{st} + X_t = M_t ,
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_t$
\end_inset

 is current net income. Notice that consumption expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $E_t = M_t - X_t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
begin{proposition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The indirect utility and expenditure functions associated to the Bellman representation of preferences in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) are 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u(M_t, P_{gt}, P_{st};\nu_t) = V\left(\left(\nu_t P_{st}\right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}},P_{gt},P_{st}\right) 
+ \nu_t \left( M_t - \left(\nu_t P_{st}\right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}} \right)
\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
e(W_t, P_{gt}, P_{st};\nu_t) = \left(\nu_t P_{st}\right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}} + \frac{W_t}{\nu_t} - \frac{ V\left(\left(\nu_t P_{st}\right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}},P_{gt},P_{st}\right) }{\nu_t} .
\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
end{proposition}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\shape smallcaps
Proof:
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 Since by definition of an indirect utility function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{\{C_{gt},C_{st}\}:P_{gt} C_{gt} + P_{st} C_{st} = E_t} U(C_{gt}, C_{st}) = V(E_t, P_{gt}, P_{st})  ,
\]
\end_inset

optimal net investment is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
X_t = \arg\max_{X}\ V(M_t - X, P_{gt}, P_{st}) +\nu_t X = M_t - \left(\nu_t P_{st}^\chi \right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}}.
\]
\end_inset

The indirect utility function associated to the Bellman representation of preferences is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u(M_t,P_{gt},P_{st};\nu_t) = V\big(\left(\nu_t P_{st}^\chi \right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}}, P_{gt}, P_{st} \big)  +\nu_t \Big(M_t - \left(\nu_t P_{st}^\chi \right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}}\Big)
\]
\end_inset

and the expenditure function is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
e(W_t,P_{gt},P_{st};\nu_t) = \frac{W_t - V\big(\left(\nu_t P_{st}^\chi \right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}}, P_{gt}, P_{st} \big)}{\nu_t}  + \left(\nu_t P_{st}^\chi \right)^{\frac{1}{\chi-1}} . \qed
\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equivalent variation measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the Fisher and Shell principle that welfare comparisons must be done using the same preference set, let us define the hypothetical income at 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula \( z < t \)
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\widehat M_{tz} = e \Big( u\big(M_z, P_{gz}, P_{sz};\nu_t\big),P_{gt}, P_{st};\nu_t\Big) .
\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\widehat M_{tz}$
\end_inset

 is the level of income at current prices that the representative household would have needed at time 
\begin_inset Formula \( z \)
\end_inset

 to attain the utility achievable with past income and prices but evaluated using the current Bellman representation of preferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Fixed-base indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us adopt the following convention for an economy where an Office for National Statistics have recorded National Accounts data from some initial time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_0$
\end_inset

 to the current time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. In this economy, a current-base equivalent variation index, for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\{t_0,t\}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
{\cal P}_{t,s} =  \widehat m_{t,s} -  \widehat m_{t,t_0} ,
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat m_{t,z} =\log \widehat M_{tz}$
\end_inset

. Notice that the index is normalized to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{t,t_0} = 0$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{t,t} =  m_t -  \widehat m_{t,t_0}$
\end_inset

 measures welfare gains from the initial time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_0$
\end_inset

 to the current time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{t,t} -{\cal P}_{t,s} =  m_t -  \widehat m_{t,s}$
\end_inset

 welfare gains from any time 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in(t_0,t)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. Implicit on this index, the equilibrium instantaneous growth rate of the economy at 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is measured by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:BBEVgrowth}
\frac{\partial{\cal P}_{t,s}}{\partial s} = \frac{\partial \widehat m_{t,s}} {\partial s}  .%= 
%\frac{ \left( \frac{m_s}{p_s} - \frac{\lambda}{\nu_t} \right) p_t g_k}{\widehat m_{t,s}} .
\end{equation}
\end_inset

As we show below, the instantaneous growth rate at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 of the current-base equivalent variation index, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial{\cal P}_{t,s}}{\partial s}|_{s=t} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%= (1-
\backslash
lambda s_c) g_k$ 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 is equal to the Divisia index at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%, defined as $g^{
\backslash
text{D}}=s_c g_c + (1-s_c) g_x$. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $s<t$
\end_inset

, the instantaneous growth rate is lower than the Divisia index and declines as the welfare evaluation refers to a more distant point in the past. (prove it) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%In fact, the growth rate as measured by the current-base BBEV index in (
\backslash
ref{eq:BBEVgrowth}) may become negative, since it evaluates the past using current preferences, $
\backslash
nu_t$ is fixed, but income measured in units of the investment good, $
\backslash
frac{m_s}{p_s}$, declines at the rate $g_k$ when moving back to the past.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

